Class PrimitiveCollection

extends java.lang.Object
implements com.telenav.kivakit.kernel.interfaces.naming.NamedObject, com.telenav.kivakit.kernel.interfaces.lifecycle.Initializable, com.telenav.kivakit.kernel.interfaces.numeric.Sized, com.telenav.kivakit.kernel.language.collections.CompressibleCollection, com.esotericsoftware.kryo.KryoSerializable
    Base class for all primitive collections, which come in two types:

    One-Dimensional Collections

    One-dimensional collections have only one key (or index) and their size is configured with initialSize(Estimate) and maximumSize(Maximum). Examples of one-dimensional collections include ByteArray, IntArray and LongToLongMap), since only one key is needed to access data in each case. Note that "split" versions of arrays and maps (to avoid allocating large contiguous blocks of memory that make the garbage collector's job harder) like SplitIntArray and SplitLongToIntMap are also one-dimensional even though they have child collections internally because they still only require a single key.

    Two-Dimensional Collections

    Two-dimensional collections have two keys (or indexes) and the second dimension can be configured with initialChildSize(Count) and maximumChildSize(Maximum). Examples of two-dimensional collections include ByteArrayArray and LongToLongMultiMap. The first key gets access to a child collection (usually an array or list) and the second key gets access to the data.

    Default Sizes

    • maximumSize = Integer.MAXIMUM
    • initialSize = 256
    • childSize = 65,536
    • maximumChildSize = 65,536

    The current size of the collection can be retrieved with Sized.size() or as a Count object with count(). For convenience, isEmpty() returns true when size() is zero.

    Primitive collections can optionally have a value selected to represent no value or 'null'. The methods nullX(value) can be used to specify this null value for type X and nullX() can be used to retrieve it. In cases where a null value is not desired, for example in a collection of bytes that includes the value Byte.MIN_VALUE (-128), the hasNullX(boolean) methods can be used to specify this and the hasNullX() method can be used to determine if there is a null value for type X.

    Default Null Values

    • hasNullLong = true
    • hasNullInt = true
    • hasNullShort = true
    • hasNullChar = true
    • hasNullChar = true
    • nullLong = 0
    • nullInt = 0
    • nullShort = 0
    • nullChar = 0
    • nullByte = 0

    The default value for null is always zero, as shown above. This allows for better performance since Java always zeroes out new data structures like arrays. However, if zero is a desired element value, it will be necessary to pick a different null value, or to specify that there is none. Note that collections may specify more than one null value, for example a LongToIntMap can specify a null long value and a null int value.

    PrimitiveCollections are KryoSerializable and CompressibleCollection. Freezing objects can reduce space to save memory, although this will typically slow access a small amount.

    Tracing of allocations can be enabled through Debug using -DKIVAKIT_DEBUG=PrimitiveCollection and details on allocation-related activities can be increased with:

    Java Properties

    • KIVAKIT_LOG_ALLOCATIONS - log all allocations greater than the minimum size
    • KIVAKIT_LOG_ALLOCATIONS_MINIMUM_SIZE - the minimum size to log (see Bytes, default is 64k)
    • KIVAKIT_LOG_ALLOCATION_STACK_TRACES - log stack traces for allocations
    All of these debugging options are expensive and should only be used during debugging.
    Author:
    jonathanl (shibo)
